                                                                                 Hardware Description

The PIC18F-Based IoT Development Board is a compact embedded hardware platform designed for sensor data acquisition, signal processing, wireless communication, and real-time monitoring applications. The board integrates a PIC18F microcontroller, analog signal conditioning circuits, Wi-Fi connectivity, display interface, digital I/O expansion, and industrial-grade power management into a single PCB.

1. Power Supply Section

The board operates from a 24V DC input supply. The input stage consists of a fuse, varistor, and filtering components that protect the system against overcurrent, voltage surges, and electrical noise. The regulated power rails are generated using a 7805 voltage regulator for 5V devices and an AMS1117-3.3 voltage regulator for 3.3V peripherals. These supplies power the microcontroller, Wi-Fi module, operational amplifiers, LCD display, and other onboard components.

2. Microcontroller Unit

The central processing unit of the board is a PIC18F series microcontroller. It performs sensor data acquisition, analog-to-digital conversion, peripheral control, communication management, and system monitoring. The controller interfaces with all major hardware modules including analog inputs, digital I/O, LCD display, Wi-Fi module, LEDs, buzzer, and communication headers.

3. Analog Signal Conditioning Circuit

The board incorporates LM358 operational amplifier circuits to condition low-level sensor signals before they are processed by the microcontroller's ADC. These amplifier stages improve signal quality, reduce noise, and enhance measurement accuracy. The conditioned outputs are connected to the analog input channels of the PIC18F microcontroller.

4. Analog Input Interface

Multiple analog input channels are provided to interface with sensors such as temperature sensors, pressure sensors, gas sensors, current sensors, voltage sensors, and other analog transducers. The analog signals are first processed by the LM358 amplifier circuits and then converted into digital values by the PIC18F ADC module.

5. Digital Input/Output Interface

Dedicated digital I/O headers are available for connecting switches, relays, indicators, actuators, and external digital modules. These pins can be configured as either inputs or outputs depending on the application requirements.

6. Wi-Fi Communication Module

Wireless connectivity is achieved through the ESP-01 module based on the ESP8266 Wi-Fi chipset. The module communicates with the PIC18F microcontroller through UART and enables remote monitoring, cloud connectivity, IoT integration, and wireless data transmission.

7. LCD Display Interface

An onboard LCD display interface provides real-time visualization of sensor values, system status information, communication status, and user notifications. The display enhances user interaction and allows standalone operation without requiring a computer connection.

8. Communication Interfaces

The board supports multiple communication protocols including UART, SPI, and I²C. These interfaces allow easy integration with sensors, displays, memory devices, communication modules, and external controllers.

9. Status Indication Circuit

Visual and audible feedback is provided through LEDs and a buzzer. The LEDs indicate power status, communication activity, and system operation, while the buzzer generates alarms and notifications during fault conditions or predefined events.

10. Oscillator and Reset Circuit

A crystal oscillator provides a stable clock source for accurate microcontroller operation. The reset circuit consists of a push-button switch, pull-up resistor, and capacitor network, ensuring reliable system startup and manual reset functionality.

